Chapter 1 – Introduction

1.1 The Problem of Fragmented Perception

Modern robotic systems perceive the environment through multiple sensors (vision, audio, LiDAR, haptics) but fail to integrate these inputs into a coherent, continuous, and actionable representation of reality. This fragmentation leads to perceptual fragmentation and context collapse: loss of temporal coherence, misinterpretation of complex scenes, action errors, and poor generalization. A robot may detect a cup but not infer that it could fall, contains liquid, or that a human may interact with it.

Mathematical formulation. Let the true world state be S_t \in \mathcal{S} (unobservable). The robot receives multimodal observations O_t = (O_t^{\text{vis}}, O_t^{\text{aud}}, O_t^{\text{hap}}, \dots) \in \mathcal{O} and executes actions A_t \in \mathcal{A}. A Partially Observable Markov Decision Process (POMDP) defines the belief state

b_t(s) = P(S_t = s \mid O_{1:t}, A_{1:t-1}),

updated via the Bayes filter:

b_{t+1}(s') = \eta \cdot \Omega(o_{t+1} \mid s', a_t) \sum_{s} T(s' \mid s, a_t) b_t(s),

with transition T and observation function \Omega. Exact inference is intractable due to high-dimensional, multimodal \mathcal{O} and large \mathcal{S}. Deep reinforcement learning approaches integrating POMDP formulations have recently shown improvements in scalability and adaptability, though unresolved challenges of robustness and sim-to-real transfer remain.

1.2 Research Gap and Core Thesis

No existing architecture jointly solves the continuous multimodal belief update with:

· Sub‑100 ms latency,
· Long‑horizon coherence (\ge 1000 steps),
· Continual learning without catastrophic forgetting,
· Causal reasoning and intuitive physics.

Recent benchmarks reveal that even state-of-the-art deep learning models perform at chance levels (50%) on intuitive physics tasks, in stark contrast to near-perfect human performance, underscoring the fundamental gap between current models and human-like physical understanding. Moreover, a sweeping 2025 manifesto from Meta AI argues that any meaningful embodied agent must learn a compact, predictive model of both the physical and the mental worlds it inhabits, identifying world models as the "missing middle" of embodied AI.

Core Thesis. Extend Dreamer‑style Recurrent State‑Space Models (RSSMs) with (i) a dynamic graph neural scene graph (GNSG) for entity‑centric relational reasoning, (ii) a memory‑augmented transformer (MAT) for long‑term memory, and (iii) a self‑supervised predictive objective that enforces physical symmetries. The resulting Neural World Simulation Engine (NWSE) provides a unified latent belief that supports planning and intuitive physics purely through mathematical structure.

1.3 Contributions (Theoretical)

1. A unified generative model and variational lower bound (ELBO) that integrates multimodal observations, rewards, and dynamic scene graphs, building upon the RSSM architecture established in DreamerV3 where the primary loss is a variational ELBO decomposed into reconstruction, reward prediction, and dual KL divergences with "free-bits" clipping.
2. A proof that the graph‑structured latent reduces belief entropy by at least the mutual information with the previous graph (Theorem 2, strengthened via Information Bottleneck).
3. A proof that the GNN message‑passing is equivariant under the Euclidean group E(3), ensuring physically consistent predictions, drawing on recent advances in spherical equivariant graph transformers where predictions must respect the rotational symmetries inherent in physics.
4. A memory‑augmented RSSM with surprise‑driven writes and a bound on retrieval fidelity (Johnson–Lindenstrauss).
5. A Lyapunov stability analysis for the recurrent deterministic state, guaranteeing boundedness even with infinite memory writes, connecting to recent work on output contraction analysis of discrete-time nonlinear systems with applications to RNNs.
6. A complexity analysis (O(T \log N_m) temporal, O(K^2) spatial) that satisfies real‑time constraints without physical tests.

1.4 Structure of the Dissertation

· Chapter 2: Literature review (POMDPs, RSSMs, graph neural networks, memory‑augmented transformers, self‑supervised learning).
· Chapter 3: Proposed architecture – full mathematical definition, generative model, inference, ELBO derivation, and equivariance proofs.
· Chapter 4: Theoretical analysis – information bottleneck, entropy bounds, memory retrieval guarantees, Lyapunov stability.
· Chapter 5: Collected proofs (detailed derivations of all theorems).
· Chapter 6: Discussion – edge cases, sensitivity analysis, limitations, ethical considerations.
· Chapter 7: Conclusion – summary of mathematical contributions and future theoretical directions.

