Chapter 3 – Proposed Architecture: Neural World Simulation Engine (NWSE)

Enhanced with Verified Mathematical Foundations and Proof Sketches

This chapter presents the complete mathematical formulation of the proposed Neural World Simulation Engine (NWSE). The architecture integrates four components: (i) a multimodal encoder that maps raw sensor streams into a joint latent representation, (ii) a dynamic graph neural scene graph (GNSG) that maintains entity‑centric structure, (iii) a memory‑augmented recurrent state‑space model (MA‑RSSM) that propagates beliefs over time, and (iv) a self‑supervised predictive objective that enables intuitive physics and continual learning. We provide the full generative model, inference procedure, training objectives, and theoretical guarantees, cross‑referencing the detailed proofs in Appendices B–I.

---

3.1 Notation and Overview

Let

· \mathbf{o}_t \in \mathbb{R}^{D_{\text{sensor}}} be the multimodal observation (e.g., RGB image, audio waveform, haptic signal),
· \mathbf{a}_t \in \mathbb{R}^{D_{\text{act}}} the action,
· r_t \in \mathbb{R} the (optional) reward,
· c_t \in \{0,1\} the continuation flag (1 if episode continues, 0 if terminal).

The NWSE maintains a joint latent belief composed of:

· Deterministic recurrent state \mathbf{h}_t \in \mathbb{R}^{D_h},
· Stochastic categorical latent \mathbf{z}_t – as in DreamerV3 (Hafner et al., 2023), we use 32 independent categorical distributions each with 32 classes (i.e., 32 one‑hot vectors concatenated),
· Dynamic scene graph \mathcal{G}_t = (\mathcal{V}_t, \mathcal{E}_t) with node descriptors \mathbf{l}_v^{(t)} \in \mathbb{R}^{D_l} and poses \mathbf{p}_v^{(t)} \in SE(3), and edge transforms \mathbf{T}_{uv} \in SE(3) (relative pose),
· Memory matrix \mathbf{M}_t \in \mathbb{R}^{N_m \times D_m} (external differentiable memory).

The overall generative model and variational posterior follow the RSSM architecture of DreamerV3, extended with graph and memory latents.

---

3.2 Multimodal Encoder and Graph Construction

3.2.1 Modality‑Specific Encoding

Each modality is processed by a dedicated encoder (CNN for vision, 1D CNN for audio, MLP for haptics) producing embeddings \mathbf{e}_t^{\text{vis}}, \mathbf{e}_t^{\text{aud}}, \mathbf{e}_t^{\text{hap}}. A cross‑attention fusion layer combines them into a joint observation embedding \mathbf{x}_t:

\mathbf{x}_t = \text{CrossAttn}\bigl( Q = \text{Linear}(\mathbf{e}_t^{\text{vis}}),\; K = \text{Linear}(\mathbf{e}_t^{\text{aud}}),\; V = \text{Linear}(\mathbf{e}_t^{\text{hap}}) \bigr) \in \mathbb{R}^{D_x}.

This follows standard practice in multimodal robotics (e.g., MomaGraph‑R1, Ju et al., 2025).

3.2.2 Object Discovery and Initial Graph

An object discovery module (e.g., Slot Attention, or the segmentation head of MomaGraph) segments the visual input into K_t object slots, each producing an initial pose \tilde{\mathbf{p}}_v and descriptor \tilde{\mathbf{l}}_v. These form the initial graph \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_t. The number of nodes K_t can change over time (objects entering or leaving the scene).

3.2.3 Graph Refinement via Equivariant Message Passing

We refine the initial graph using an E(3)-equivariant Graph Neural Network (EGNN, Satorras et al., 2021; Brandstetter et al., 2022). For each node v with coordinates \mathbf{p}_v^{(t)} (in world frame) and node features \mathbf{l}_v^{(t,0)} = \tilde{\mathbf{l}}_v, the EGNN update is:

\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{m}_{uv} &= \phi_e\left(\mathbf{l}_u^{(l-1)}, \mathbf{l}_v^{(l-1)}, \|\mathbf{p}_u^{(t)} - \mathbf{p}_v^{(t)}\|^2, \mathbf{e}_{uv}\right), \\
\mathbf{l}_v^{(l)} &= \phi_h\left(\mathbf{l}_v^{(l-1)}, \sum_{u \neq v} \mathbf{m}_{uv}\right), \\
\mathbf{p}_v^{(t,l)} &= \mathbf{p}_v^{(t,l-1)} + \sum_{u \neq v} (\mathbf{p}_v^{(t,l-1)} - \mathbf{p}_u^{(t,l-1)}) \, \phi_x(\mathbf{m}_{uv}),
\end{aligned}

where \phi_e, \phi_h, \phi_x are MLPs and \mathbf{e}_{uv} encodes the relation type (e.g., “support”, “attached”). After L layers, we set \mathbf{l}_v^{(t)} = \mathbf{l}_v^{(L)} and \mathbf{p}_v^{(t)} = \mathbf{p}_v^{(t,L)}. The EGNN is E(3)-equivariant by construction (see Theorem 3.1 and Appendix C.2).

---

3.3 Memory‑Augmented Recurrent State‑Space Model (MA‑RSSM)

3.3.1 Deterministic State with Memory Read

We augment the RSSM deterministic path with an external memory \mathbf{M}_{t-1}. At each step, we read from memory using cross‑attention with the previous deterministic state as query:

\mathbf{r}_t = \text{CrossAttn}\bigl( Q = \mathbf{h}_{t-1},\; K = \mathbf{M}_{t-1},\; V = \mathbf{M}_{t-1} \bigr) \in \mathbb{R}^{D_m}.

The deterministic state is updated via a GRU:

\mathbf{h}_t = \text{GRU}_{\phi}\bigl( \mathbf{h}_{t-1},\; [\mathbf{z}_{t-1},\; \mathbf{a}_{t-1},\; \mathbf{r}_t] \bigr).

Here [\cdot,\cdot] denotes concatenation.

3.3.2 Stochastic Latent State

We use the same categorical posterior/prior as DreamerV3. The prior and posterior are factorized over 32 independent categorical variables:

p_\phi(\hat{\mathbf{z}}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) = \prod_{k=1}^{32} \text{Cat}(\hat{z}_{t,k} \mid \boldsymbol{\pi}_{t,k}^{\text{prior}}), \qquad
q_\phi(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{x}_t) = \prod_{k=1}^{32} \text{Cat}(z_{t,k} \mid \boldsymbol{\pi}_{t,k}^{\text{post}}).

The parameters \boldsymbol{\pi}_{t}^{\text{prior}} and \boldsymbol{\pi}_{t}^{\text{post}} are computed by small MLPs from \mathbf{h}_t and [\mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{x}_t] respectively.

3.3.3 Surprise‑Driven Memory Write

We compute the surprise d_t = \mathrm{KL}\bigl[ q_\phi(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{x}_t) \;\|\; p_\phi(\hat{\mathbf{z}}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) \bigr]. If d_t > \tau (a threshold hyperparameter), we write a key–value pair into memory:

\mathbf{k}_t = \text{MLP}_k([\mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t]), \quad \mathbf{v}_t = \text{MLP}_v([\mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t]).

Memory is updated using a least‑recently‑used (LRU) replacement policy. The read and write operations are differentiable when using softmax weights, but we follow the common practice of treating the discrete LRU as an approximation of a variational memory posterior (see Appendix D.3 for the bounded gap).

3.3.4 Generative Model

The model reconstructs the observation, reward, continuation flag, and the scene graph:

\begin{aligned}
\hat{\mathbf{x}}_t &\sim p_\phi(\hat{\mathbf{x}}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) = \mathcal{N}(\mu_x(\mathbf{h}_t,\mathbf{z}_t), \sigma_x^2 I), \\
\hat{r}_t &\sim p_\phi(\hat{r}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) = \text{Laplace}(r_t \mid \mu_r(\mathbf{h}_t,\mathbf{z}_t), b_r), \\
\hat{c}_t &\sim p_\phi(\hat{c}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) = \text{Bernoulli}(c_t \mid \text{sigmoid}(\mu_c(\mathbf{h}_t,\mathbf{z}_t))), \\
\hat{\mathcal{G}}_t &\sim p_\phi(\hat{\mathcal{G}}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) = \prod_{v \in \mathcal{V}_t} \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{l}_v^{(t)} \mid \mu_{l,v}(\mathbf{h}_t,\mathbf{z}_t), \sigma_l^2 I) \times \prod_{(u,v)\in\mathcal{E}_t} \text{vMF}(\mathbf{T}_{uv} \mid \mu_{T,uv}(\mathbf{h}_t,\mathbf{z}_t), \kappa),
\end{aligned}

where vMF denotes the von Mises–Fisher distribution on SO(3). The means are outputs of MLPs.

---

3.4 Graph Dynamics as Part of the Latent State

The scene graph is not only an output but also part of the latent state that influences future predictions. We model graph dynamics with a Graph Recurrent Network (GRN) that takes the previous graph \mathcal{G}_{t-1}, the action \mathbf{a}_{t-1}, and the current deterministic state \mathbf{h}_t (which already incorporates memory read) and outputs a predicted graph \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_t:

\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_t = \text{GRN}(\mathcal{G}_{t-1}, \mathbf{a}_{t-1}, \mathbf{h}_t).

The GRN uses an EGNN to update node features and poses:

\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{m}_{uv} &= \psi_e\left( \mathbf{l}_u^{(t-1)}, \mathbf{l}_v^{(t-1)}, \|\mathbf{p}_u^{(t-1)} - \mathbf{p}_v^{(t-1)}\|^2, \mathbf{a}_{t-1} \right), \\
\tilde{\mathbf{l}}_v^{(t)} &= \psi_h\left( \mathbf{l}_v^{(t-1)}, \sum_{u \neq v} \mathbf{m}_{uv} \right), \\
\tilde{\mathbf{p}}_v^{(t)} &= \mathbf{p}_v^{(t-1)} + \sum_{u \neq v} (\mathbf{p}_v^{(t-1)} - \mathbf{p}_u^{(t-1)}) \, \psi_x(\mathbf{m}_{uv}).
\end{aligned}

This update is E(3)-equivariant (same proof as for the encoder EGNN). The predicted graph \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_t is then used in the graph KL term of the ELBO (Section 3.5) and as a prior for the inferred graph \mathcal{G}_t.

---

3.5 Unified ELBO with Graph and Memory Regularization

Let \mathbf{Z}_t = (\mathbf{z}_t, \mathcal{G}_t, \mathbf{M}_t) be the joint latent. The generative model factorizes as:

p(\mathbf{o}_{1:T}, r_{1:T}, \mathcal{G}_{1:T}, \mathbf{Z}_{1:T} \mid \mathbf{a}_{1:T-1}) = \prod_{t=1}^T p(\mathbf{o}_t, r_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) \, p(\mathcal{G}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) \, p(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) \, p(\mathbf{M}_t \mid \mathbf{M}_{t-1}).

The variational posterior is:

q(\mathbf{Z}_{1:T} \mid \mathbf{o}_{1:T}, \mathcal{G}_{1:T}, \mathbf{a}_{1:T-1}) = \prod_{t=1}^T q(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{x}_t) \, q(\mathcal{G}_t \mid \mathbf{o}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) \, q(\mathbf{M}_t \mid \mathbf{M}_{t-1}, \Delta_t).

Here q(\mathcal{G}_t \mid \mathbf{o}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) is implemented by the object discovery + EGNN encoder (Section 3.2). The memory posterior q(\mathbf{M}_t \mid \mathbf{M}_{t-1}, \Delta_t) is approximated by the LRU write rule (surprise‑driven) – a valid variational approximation with bounded gap (Appendix D.3).

Evidence Lower Bound (ELBO). Applying the standard VAE bound (Appendix B.1) sequentially yields:

\begin{aligned}
\log p(\mathbf{o}_{1:T}, r_{1:T} \mid \mathbf{a}_{1:T-1}) &\geq
\sum_{t=1}^T \mathbb{E}_{q} \Big[ \log p(\mathbf{o}_t, r_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) + \log p(\mathcal{G}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) \Big] \\
&\quad - \sum_{t=1}^T \mathrm{KL}\big( q(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{x}_t) \;\|\; p(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) \big) \\
&\quad - \sum_{t=1}^T \mathrm{KL}\big( q(\mathcal{G}_t \mid \mathbf{o}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) \;\|\; p(\mathcal{G}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathbf{z}_t) \big) \\
&\quad - \sum_{t=1}^T \mathbb{E}_{q} \Big[ \mathrm{KL}\big( q(\mathbf{M}_t \mid \mathbf{M}_{t-1}, \Delta_t) \;\|\; p(\mathbf{M}_t \mid \mathbf{M}_{t-1}) \big) \Big].
\end{aligned}

We apply the free‑bits clipping (DreamerV3) to the \mathbf{z}_t KL term: replace \mathrm{KL} with \max(1, \mathrm{KL}). The graph and memory KL terms can also be clipped if desired, but we keep them unclipped to encourage accurate graph prediction and efficient memory use.

Memory prior. We use a simple diffusion‑style prior:

p(\mathbf{M}_t \mid \mathbf{M}_{t-1}) = \prod_{i=1}^{N_m} \mathcal{N}\big( \mathbf{M}_t[i,:] \mid \alpha \mathbf{M}_{t-1}[i,:],\; (1-\alpha^2) \sigma_m^2 I \big),

where \alpha \in (0,1) is a decay factor. This softly forgets unused slots, preventing unbounded memory growth.

