3.6 Self‑Supervised Predictive Objective for Intuitive Physics

We add a V‑JEPA style (Bardes et al., 2024) self‑supervised loss that predicts latent representations of masked future observations. Given a sequence of observations \mathbf{o}_{1:T}, we randomly mask a subset of timesteps \mathcal{M}. The model encodes the unmasked observations into latents \mathbf{z}_t^{\text{unmasked}} using the same RSSM encoder (with stop‑gradient on the target network). A predictor network p_\phi^{\text{pred}} takes the context latents and predicts the masked latents:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{pred}} = \mathbb{E}_{\text{mask}} \left[ \sum_{t \in \mathcal{M}} \left\| \text{sg}\big( f_{\theta_{\text{EMA}}}(\mathbf{o}_{1:t}^{\text{unmasked}}) \big) - p_\phi^{\text{pred}}\big( \{\mathbf{z}_{<t}^{\text{unmasked}}\} \big) \right\|_1 \right],

where \text{sg} denotes stop‑gradient and f_{\theta_{\text{EMA}}} is an exponential moving average of the encoder. This loss forces the model to learn physical regularities (object permanence, gravity, solidity) without explicit labels. The surprise on a physically impossible video is defined as:

S_t = \left\| p_\phi^{\text{pred}}(\{\mathbf{z}_{<t}\}) - f_{\theta_{\text{EMA}}}(\mathbf{o}_{1:t}) \right\|_1,

and higher surprise indicates detection of physical violations (Bordes et al., 2025; IntPhys 2 benchmark).

