3.8 Theoretical Guarantees (Proof Sketches)

We state the main theoretical results that justify the NWSE architecture. Full proofs are provided in Appendices B–I.

Theorem 3.1 (E(3)-Equivariance of the Graph Dynamics)

Assumptions. The EGNN message functions \phi_e, \phi_h, \phi_x depend only on invariant features (distances, dot products) and the relative pose transformation is equivariant.

Statement. For any g = (\mathbf{R}, \mathbf{t}) \in E(3),

\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}(g \cdot \mathcal{G}_t, g \cdot \mathbf{a}_t) = g \cdot \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}(\mathcal{G}_t, \mathbf{a}_t),

where the action on poses is g \cdot \mathbf{p} = \mathbf{R}\mathbf{p} + \mathbf{t}, and on actions is defined appropriately (e.g., rotations for torques).

Proof sketch. The EGNN update uses only Euclidean distances and relative directions, which are invariant under rotations and translations. The GRU on invariant features preserves invariance. The parallel transport of vector features ensures equivariance. See Appendix C.2 for the full proof based on Satorras et al. (2021) and Brandstetter et al. (2022). ∎

Theorem 3.2 (Graph as Predictive Sufficient Statistic – Information Bottleneck)

Assumptions. The object discovery module minimizes the variational information bottleneck (VIB) objective:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{VIB}}(\theta) = I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - \beta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t), \quad \beta > 0.

Statement. At any stationary point \theta^*, for any alternative representation \mathbf{z}_t = g(\mathbf{o}_t),

I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) \geq I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) - \frac{1}{\beta}\bigl( I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) \bigr).

Proof sketch. Follows from the convexity of the IB functional and the data processing inequality. The VIB bound (Alemi et al., 2017) and the Markov chain \mathbf{o}_t \to \mathcal{G}_t \to \mathbf{o}_{t+1} yield the result. See Appendix I.1 and Fu et al. (AAAI 2025) for details. ∎

Theorem 3.3 (Memory Retrieval Fidelity – Johnson‑Lindenstrauss)

Assumptions. Memory keys \mathbf{k}_i \in \mathbb{R}^{D_k} are \alpha-separated: \|\mathbf{k}_i - \mathbf{k}_j\| \geq \alpha for all i \neq j. Let \Pi \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times D_k} be a random Gaussian projection with d = O(\epsilon^{-2} \log N_m).

Statement. For any query \mathbf{q}, with probability at least 1 - \delta, the nearest neighbor in the projected space \tilde{\mathbf{k}} satisfies:

\|\mathbf{q} - \tilde{\mathbf{k}}\| \leq (1 + \epsilon) \|\mathbf{q} - \mathbf{k}^*\| + \epsilon \cdot \text{diam}(\mathcal{K}),

where \mathbf{k}^* is the true nearest neighbor. The false retrieval probability is bounded by:

P(\tilde{\mathbf{k}} \neq \mathbf{k}^*) \leq N_m^2 \exp\left( -\frac{\epsilon^2 \alpha^2}{8} \right).

Proof sketch. Direct application of the Johnson‑Lindenstrauss lemma (Dasgupta & Gupta, 2003) and union bound over key pairs. See Appendix E.2 and Indyk & Motwani (1998). ∎

Theorem 3.4 (Lyapunov Stability of the Deterministic State)

Assumptions. The GRU parameters satisfy \|W_z\|_2, \|W_r\|_2, \|W_h\|_2 \leq \gamma < 1 and activation functions have Lipschitz constant 1. Memory read satisfies \|\mathbf{r}_t\| \leq B_r and input \|\mathbf{u}_t\| \leq B_u.

Statement. The recurrent map F(\mathbf{h}, \mathbf{u}) = \text{GRU}(\mathbf{h}, \mathbf{u}) is a contraction with constant \rho = \gamma + \gamma^2 < 1. For any sequence, the hidden state remains bounded:

\|\mathbf{h}_t\| \leq \rho^t \|\mathbf{h}_0\| + \frac{B_u + B_r}{1 - \rho}.

If memory writes introduce bounded perturbations \|\delta_t\| \leq \epsilon, the asymptotic bound becomes \frac{B_u + B_r + \epsilon}{1 - \rho}.

Proof sketch. The GRU update can be shown to be Lipschitz with constant \rho (Miller & Hardt, 2019; Gao et al., Neural Networks 2025). The boundedness follows from iterating the contraction inequality. See Appendix F for the full proof. ∎

