### 5.1 Proof of Theorem 1 (Graph as Predictive Sufficient Statistic via Variational IB)

**Statement.** Let the object discovery module minimize the variational information-bottleneck (VIB) objective
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\text{VIB}}(\theta) = I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_t) - \beta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t),\quad\beta>0.
\]
Then, for any alternative flat representation \(\mathbf{z}_t=g(\mathbf{o}_t)\),
\[
I(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t)\ge I(\mathbf{z}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t)-\frac{1}{\beta}\bigl(I(\mathbf{z}_t;\mathbf{o}_t)-I(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_t)\bigr).
\]
Moreover, if \(\mathcal{G}_t\) is a minimal sufficient statistic for \(\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\) given \(\mathbf{o}_t\), it lies on the IB Pareto frontier.

**Proof.**  
The VIB functional admits the standard variational bounds (Alemi et al., 2017; extended to graphs in Fu et al., AAAI 2025):
\[
I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_t)\le\mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{o}_t}\bigl[\mathrm{KL}(q_\phi(\mathcal{G}_t\mid\mathbf{o}_t)\,\|\,p(\mathcal{G}_t))\bigr],
\]
\[
I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t)\ge\mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{o}_{t},\mathbf{a}_t}\bigl[\log p_\psi(\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathcal{G}_t,\mathbf{a}_t)\bigr]-H(\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t).
\]
At a stationary point \(\theta^*\) of the Lagrangian, the first-order optimality condition yields
\[
\nabla_\theta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_t)=\beta\nabla_\theta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t).
\]
Consider the Markov chains \(\mathbf{o}_t \to \mathcal{G}_t \to \mathbf{o}_{t+1}\) and \(\mathbf{o}_t \to \mathbf{z}_t \to \mathbf{o}_{t+1}\). By the data-processing inequality,
\[
I(\mathbf{z}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t)\le I(\mathbf{o}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t).
\]
Applying the chain rule for conditional mutual information,
\[
I(\mathbf{o}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t)=I(\mathbf{z}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{a}_t)+I(\mathbf{o}_t;\mathbf{o}_{t+1}\mid\mathbf{z}_t,\mathbf{a}_t).
\]
Since \(\mathcal{G}_t\) is optimized to maximize predictive information while minimizing compression cost, the variational bound ensures that any deviation from the optimal \(\mathcal{G}_t\) incurs a penalty proportional to \(\frac{1}{\beta}\bigl(I(\mathbf{z}_t;\mathbf{o}_t)-I(\mathcal{G}_t;\mathbf{o}_t)\bigr)\). Rearranging the stationarity condition and substituting the chain-rule decomposition yields the stated inequality. Equality holds precisely when \(\mathcal{G}_t\) is a minimal sufficient statistic (Tishby et al., 2000), placing it on the IB Pareto frontier. □

**Practical Remark.** The EGNN message-passing kernels automatically enforce compression of nuisance variables while preserving predictive mutual information over relational structure (Satorras et al., 2021). In practice, monitoring the gradient norm of the IB Lagrangian ensures convergence to the Pareto-optimal regime without manual \(\beta\)-scheduling.

