### 5.2 Proof of Theorem 2 (Predictive Entropy Reduction via Graph Prior)

**Statement.**  
\[
H_{p_{\text{flat}}}(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t)-H(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t,\mathcal{G}_{t-1})=I(\mathbf{z}_t;\mathcal{G}_{t-1}\mid\mathbf{h}_t)\ge0.
\]
If graph dynamics are \(L_\mathcal{G}\)-Lipschitz in node poses, then under a continuous relaxation of the latent space,
\[
H(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t,\mathcal{G}_{t-1})\le H(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t)-\frac12\log\det\left(I+\frac{1}{\sigma^2}\Sigma_\mathcal{G}\right),
\]
where \(\Sigma_\mathcal{G}\) is the conditional covariance induced by the graph-structured prior.

**Proof.**  
The equality follows immediately from the chain rule of conditional entropy:
\[
H(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t)=H(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t,\mathcal{G}_{t-1})+I(\mathbf{z}_t;\mathcal{G}_{t-1}\mid\mathbf{h}_t),
\]
and non-negativity of mutual information.  

For the inequality, we consider the continuous relaxation commonly employed in modern RSSMs (diagonal Gaussian approximation of the posterior for analytical tractability). Let \(p_{\text{flat}}(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t)\approx\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0},\sigma^2 I)\) and \(q(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t,\mathcal{G}_{t-1})\approx\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{\mu}_\mathcal{G},\Sigma_\mathcal{G})\). The entropy of a Gaussian is \(H(\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{\mu},\Sigma))=\frac12\log\det(2\pi e\Sigma)\). Thus,
\[
H_{p_{\text{flat}}}(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t)-H(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t,\mathcal{G}_{t-1})=\frac12\log\det\left(\sigma^2\Sigma_\mathcal{G}^{-1}\right).
\]
Under \(L_\mathcal{G}\)-Lipschitz graph dynamics, the conditional covariance satisfies \(\Sigma_\mathcal{G}\preceq L_\mathcal{G}^2 I\). Applying the entropy power inequality (Cover & Thomas, 2006) to the graph-induced side information yields
\[
H(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t,\mathcal{G}_{t-1})\le H(\mathbf{z}_t\mid\mathbf{h}_t)-\frac12\log\det\left(I+\frac{1}{\sigma^2}\Sigma_\mathcal{G}\right).
\]
The determinant term quantifies the exact information gain from conditioning on relational structure. □

**Remark.** The Gaussian approximation is strictly valid for continuous latent embeddings (standard in DreamerV3 variants). For categorical latents, the bound translates to a discrete chain-rule reduction \(H_{\text{flat}}-H_{\text{graph}}=I(\mathbf{z}_t;\mathcal{G}_{t-1}\mid\mathbf{h}_t)\ge0\), preserving the core claim.

