### 5.3 Proof of Theorem 3 (E(3)-Equivariant Recurrent Dynamics)

**Statement.** Under decomposition into invariant scalars \(\mathbf{s}_v\) and equivariant vectors \(\mathbf{v}_v\), with \(E(3)\)-equivariant message kernels and parallel-transport updates, the Graph Recurrent Network (GRN) satisfies
\[
\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}(g\cdot\mathcal{G}_t,g\cdot\mathbf{a}_t)=g\cdot\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}(\mathcal{G}_t,\mathbf{a}_t)\quad\forall g=(\mathbf{R},\mathbf{t})\in E(3).
\]
If trained with symmetry-penalized loss \(\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}\), the expected violation of linear momentum conservation satisfies
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[\left\|\sum_v m_v\Delta\mathbf{v}_v-\mathbf{F}_{\text{ext}}\Delta t\right\|\right]\le \mathcal{O}\bigl(\sqrt{\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}}\bigr).
\]

**Proof.**  
Define the group action \(g\cdot\mathbf{p}=\mathbf{Rp}+\mathbf{t}\), \(g\cdot\mathbf{s}=\mathbf{s}\), \(g\cdot\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{Rv}\). Euclidean distances satisfy \(\|g\cdot\mathbf{p}_u-g\cdot\mathbf{p}_v\|=\|\mathbf{p}_u-\mathbf{p}_v\|\), hence invariant. The message function \(\phi_{\text{msg}}\) depends solely on invariants → invariant. The vector update uses parallel transport: \(\mathbf{v}_v^{(t)}=\mathbf{R}_{uv}^{(t)}\mathbf{v}_u^{(t-1)}+\text{MLP}_{\text{vec}}(\mathbf{s}_u,\mathbf{s}_v,\|\mathbf{p}_u-\mathbf{p}_v\|)\). Since \(\mathbf{R}_{uv}^{(t)}\) transforms as \(\mathbf{R}\mathbf{R}_{uv}^{(t)}\), the update commutes with the group action. The GRU operates exclusively on invariant scalars, preserving invariance. Composition of invariant and equivariant maps yields full \(E(3)\)-equivariance of \(\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}\).

For the conservation bound, expand the symmetry penalty around the identity \(g=\mathbb{I}\):
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}=\mathbb{E}_g\|\hat{\mathbf{o}}_{t+1}-g^{-1}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{o}}_{t+1}(g\cdot\mathcal{G}_t)\|^2.
\]
Taylor expansion to second order yields a quadratic form in the infinitesimal generators of \(E(3)\). By discrete Noether correspondence (Marsden & West, 2001; Brandstetter et al., 2022), the gradient of \(\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}\) bounds the residual in the discrete momentum update. Hence the conservation error scales as \(\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}})\). □

**Benchmark Context.** While recent equivariant architectures (e.g., VN-EGNN, Sestak et al., 2025) achieve state-of-the-art on structured geometric tasks, IntPhys 2 (Bordes et al., arXiv:2506.09849) confirms that purely video-based predictors remain near chance (\(\le 60\%\)) on complex physical violations. The explicit \(E(3)\)-equivariant graph prior provides a mathematically grounded inductive bias that bypasses reliance on pixel-level correlation learning.

