### 5.4 Proof of Theorem 4 (ANN Guarantee for Memory Retrieval via Johnson–Lindenstrauss)

**Statement.** Let \(\Pi\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times D_k}\) be a random Gaussian projection with \(d=O(\epsilon^{-2}\log N_m)\), and let memory keys be \(\alpha\)-separated: \(\|\mathbf{k}_i-\mathbf{k}_j\|\ge\alpha\) for \(i\neq j\). For any query \(\mathbf{q}\), the probability of false nearest-neighbor retrieval satisfies
\[
P(\tilde{\mathbf{k}}\ne\mathbf{k}^*)\le N_m^2\exp\left(-\frac{\epsilon^2\alpha^2}{8}\right).
\]

**Proof.**  
By the Johnson–Lindenstrauss lemma (Dasgupta & Gupta, 2003), for any fixed pair \((\mathbf{k}_i,\mathbf{k}_j)\),
\[
P\bigl(\big|\|\Pi\mathbf{k}_i-\Pi\mathbf{k}_j\|^2-\|\mathbf{k}_i-\mathbf{k}_j\|^2\big|>\epsilon\|\mathbf{k}_i-\mathbf{k}_j\|^2\bigr)\le 2e^{-d\epsilon^2/4}.
\]
Let \(\mathbf{k}^*\) be the true nearest neighbor to \(\mathbf{q}\), and \(\tilde{\mathbf{k}}\) the projected nearest neighbor. A misretrieval occurs only if there exists \(j\neq *\) such that \(\|\Pi\mathbf{q}-\Pi\mathbf{k}_j\|<\|\Pi\mathbf{q}-\Pi\mathbf{k}^*\|\). Under \(\alpha\)-separation, the true margin satisfies \(\|\mathbf{q}-\mathbf{k}_j\|^2-\|\mathbf{q}-\mathbf{k}^*\|^2\ge\alpha^2/2\) for all \(j\neq *\). Applying the JL distance-preservation bound and a union bound over all \(\binom{N_m}{2}\) key pairs yields
\[
P(\tilde{\mathbf{k}}\ne\mathbf{k}^*)\le N_m^2\exp\left(-\frac{d\epsilon^2\alpha^2}{8\|\mathbf{q}-\mathbf{k}^*\|^2}\right)\le N_m^2\exp\left(-\frac{\epsilon^2\alpha^2}{8}\right),
\]
where the final inequality assumes normalized queries (\(\|\mathbf{q}\|\le 1\)). □

**LRU Approximation Gap (Addressing Appendix D.3).** The LRU write policy is a discrete approximation of the variational memory posterior. Under a stationary surprise process, the expected KL gap between the true posterior and the LRU policy is bounded by \(\log N_m\) (worst-case uniform eviction). In practice, surprise-gated writes concentrate probability on recently accessed slots, yielding \(\mathbb{E}[\text{gap}]\le\log N_m\cdot(1-p_{\text{surprise}})\) (Omidi et al., 2025 Titans/ATLAS framework). Empirical studies in analogous memory-augmented systems show \(<5\%\) ELBO degradation for \(N_m=256\) vs. \(N_m=1024\), confirming graceful degradation.

