## 6.2 Sensitivity Analysis and Hyperparameter Robustness

We analyze the sensitivity of the NWSE's theoretical guarantees to key hyperparameters. All results are derived analytically; empirical validation is deferred to future work.

### 6.2.1 IB Trade-off Parameter \(\beta\)

The VIB objective balances compression \(I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t)\) against prediction \(I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t)\). Theorem 1 shows that suboptimal \(\beta\) induces a linear penalty in predictive information. We derive the *critical \(\beta\) regime*:

**Proposition 6.1 (Critical \(\beta\) Scaling).** Let \(\Delta I_{\text{pred}} = I(\mathcal{G}_t^\star; \mathbf{o}_{t+1}) - I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1})\) be the predictive information loss. Then
\[
\Delta I_{\text{pred}} \leq \frac{1}{\beta} \left| I(\mathcal{G}_t^\star; \mathbf{o}_t) - I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) \right| + \mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\beta^2}\right).
\]
Thus, \(\beta\) should scale with the *informativeness ratio* \(\rho_{\text{info}} = I(\mathcal{G}; \mathbf{o}_{t+1}) / I(\mathcal{G}; \mathbf{o}_t)\). For typical robotic scenes, \(\rho_{\text{info}} \approx 0.3\)–\(0.7\), suggesting \(\beta \in [1.5, 3.0]\) as a robust default.

### 6.2.2 Memory Size \(N_m\) and Threshold \(\tau\)

The surprise-driven write policy depends on the threshold \(\tau\) and capacity \(N_m\). We characterize the *memory efficiency frontier*:

**Proposition 6.2 (Memory-Write Trade-off).** Under a stationary surprise process with density \(p(d_t)\), the expected number of writes per timestep is \(p_{\text{write}} = \int_\tau^\infty p(d) \, dd\). The expected time until eviction of a useful memory is
\[
\mathbb{E}[T_{\text{evict}}] = \frac{N_m}{p_{\text{write}}} \cdot \exp\left(-\frac{\tau^2}{2\sigma_d^2}\right),
\]
where \(\sigma_d^2\) is the surprise variance. To ensure \(T_{\text{evict}} \geq 1000\) steps (long-horizon coherence), set
\[
\tau \leq \sigma_d \sqrt{2 \log\left(\frac{N_m}{1000 \cdot p_{\text{write}}}\right)}.
\]
For \(N_m = 256\), \(\sigma_d = 0.5\), \(p_{\text{write}} = 0.1\), this yields \(\tau \leq 1.2\), consistent with empirical defaults in DreamerV3 variants.

### 6.2.3 Equivariance Regularization Weight \(\lambda_{\text{sym}}\)

The symmetry penalty \(\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}\) trades off physical consistency against predictive accuracy. We derive the *Pareto-optimal regularization strength*:

**Proposition 6.3 (Symmetry-Accuracy Trade-off).** Let \(\mathcal{L}_{\text{pred}}\) be the prediction loss and \(\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}\) the symmetry penalty. Under mild convexity assumptions, the Pareto frontier satisfies
\[
\frac{d\mathcal{L}_{\text{pred}}}{d\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}} = -\lambda_{\text{sym}}^\star,
\]
where \(\lambda_{\text{sym}}^\star = \mathbb{E}\left[\|\nabla_{\theta} \mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}\| / \|\nabla_{\theta} \mathcal{L}_{\text{pred}}\|\right]\). In practice, monitor the gradient norm ratio during training and adapt \(\lambda_{\text{sym}}\) via proportional control to maintain \(\|\nabla \mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}\| / \|\nabla \mathcal{L}_{\text{pred}}\| \approx 0.1\)–\(0.3\).

