## 6.4 Practical Deployment Considerations

While this dissertation is purely theoretical, we outline considerations for eventual real-world deployment.

### 6.4.1 Computational Resource Allocation

The NWSE's complexity \(O(T \log N_m + K^2)\) permits real-time operation on edge hardware, but resource allocation matters:

**Proposition 6.7 (Latency-Accuracy Trade-off).** Let \(L_{\text{total}}\) be the latency budget. Allocating fractions \(\alpha_G, \alpha_M, \alpha_R\) to graph updates, memory reads, and recurrent dynamics respectively, the end-to-end prediction error scales as
\[
\mathcal{E}_{\text{pred}} \propto \alpha_G^{-1} + \alpha_M^{-1/2} + \alpha_R^{-1},
\]
under standard approximation bounds. Optimizing \(\alpha_\ast\) via convex programming yields the Pareto-optimal allocation for a given \(L_{\text{total}}\).

### 6.4.2 Sim-to-Real Transfer Without Experiments

Theoretical sim-to-real guarantees require bounding the distributional shift:

**Definition 6.4 (Latent-Space Discrepancy).** Let \(p_{\text{sim}}(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t)\) and \(p_{\text{real}}(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t)\) be the latent posteriors in simulation and reality. The latent discrepancy is
\[
\Delta_{\text{latent}} = \sup_{\mathbf{h}_t} \mathrm{KL}\bigl(p_{\text{real}}(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) \,\|\, p_{\text{sim}}(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t)\bigr).
\]

**Proposition 6.8 (Discrepancy-Aware Planning).** If \(\Delta_{\text{latent}} \leq \delta\), then the suboptimality of policies trained in simulation and deployed in reality is bounded by
\[
J_{\text{real}}(\pi_{\text{sim}}) - J_{\text{real}}(\pi_{\text{real}}^\star) \leq \frac{2\gamma \delta}{(1-\gamma)^2} + \mathcal{O}(\delta^2),
\]
where \(\gamma\) is the discount factor. Thus, minimizing \(\Delta_{\text{latent}}\) via domain-randomized training provides a theoretical sim-to-real guarantee.

### 6.4.3 Continual Learning Without Catastrophic Forgetting

The NWSE's memory-augmented architecture supports continual adaptation, but theoretical forgetting bounds are needed:

**Proposition 6.9 (Memory-Based Forgetting Bound).** Let \(\mathcal{M}_t\) be the memory at time \(t\), and let \(\mathcal{T}_1, \mathcal{T}_2\) be two tasks. The forgetting on \(\mathcal{T}_1\) after learning \(\mathcal{T}_2\) satisfies
\[
\text{Forget}(\mathcal{T}_1 \to \mathcal{T}_2) \leq \mathrm{KL}\bigl(p(\mathcal{M}_{t_2} \mid \mathcal{T}_1, \mathcal{T}_2) \,\|\, p(\mathcal{M}_{t_1} \mid \mathcal{T}_1)\bigr) + \mathcal{O}(\epsilon_{\text{approx}}),
\]
where \(\epsilon_{\text{approx}}\) is the variational approximation error. Surprise-driven writes naturally prioritize novel information, reducing forgetting when tasks are dissimilar.

