## Appendix D: Memory-Augmented Architectures

### D.1 Differentiable Memory Formalism
**Definition D.1 (MAT Read/Write).** Read: $\mathbf{r}_t = \text{CrossAttn}(\mathbf{h}_{t-1}, \mathbf{M}_{t-1}, \mathbf{M}_{t-1})$. Write: $\mathbf{M}_t[i,:] = (1-w_t^i)\mathbf{M}_{t-1}[i,:] + w_t^i \mathbf{v}_t$, with $\mathbf{w}_t \in \Delta^{N_m-1}$.

### D.2 LRU Approximation Gap
**Theorem D.1 (Bounded Variational Gap).** Let $q^*(\mathbf{M}_t|\mathbf{M}_{t-1},\Delta_t)$ be the true posterior and $q_{\text{LRU}}$ the surprise-gated LRU approximation. Then
\[
\mathrm{KL}(q^* \parallel q_{\text{LRU}}) \leq \log N_m.
\]
Under stationary surprise process with write probability $p_w$, the expected gap concentrates as
\[
\mathbb{E}[\mathrm{KL}] \leq \log N_m \cdot (1 - p_w) + \mathcal{O}(N_m^{-1}).
\]
*Proof.* Worst case: true posterior is point mass on evicted slot, LRU assigns uniform probability over $N_m$ slots. KL = $\log N_m$. Stationary writes concentrate mass on active slots; concentration follows from Hoeffding bound on LRU counters. ∎

**Empirical Safeguard:** Use soft LRU with temperature $\tau_w \to 0$ during training, straight-through estimator at inference. Gradient bias is $\mathcal{O}(\tau_w^2)$.

