## Appendix G: Self-Supervised Predictive Coding

### G.1 V-JEPA Objective
**Definition G.1.** Masked prediction loss:
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\text{pred}} = \mathbb{E}_{\mathcal{M}} \left[ \sum_{t \in \mathcal{M}} \| \text{sg}(f_{\theta_{\text{EMA}}}(\mathbf{o}_{1:t}^{\text{unmasked}})) - p_\phi^{\text{pred}}(\{\mathbf{z}_{<t}^{\text{unmasked}}\}) \|_1 \right].
\]

### G.2 Surprise Concentration
**Theorem G.1.** Let $S_t = \| p_\phi^{\text{pred}} - f_{\theta_{\text{EMA}}} \|_1$. If predictor class $\mathcal{P}$ has Rademacher complexity $\mathfrak{R}_T(\mathcal{P}) \leq \eta$, and physical violation induces minimal latent divergence $\Delta_{\text{phys}} > 0$, then with probability $\geq 1-\delta$,
\[
\mathbb{E}[S_t | \mathcal{D}_{\text{viol}}] \geq \Delta_{\text{phys}} - 2\mathfrak{R}_T(\mathcal{P}) - \sqrt{\frac{2\log(1/\delta)}{T}}.
\]
*Proof.* $S_t$ lower-bounds KL between true and learned transition. McDiarmid's inequality bounds deviation from expectation. EMA target stabilizes variance. ∎

**Overfitting Mitigation:** Capacity regularization (predictor depth $\approx$ encoder/2), domain randomization, early stopping on validation surprise gap. Bounds hold uniformly over randomized domains.

